Colin (and members of the NEAT group),



Sorry for any trouble I&#39;m about to cause.



I would propose category theory as an underlying mathematical formalism for
this work. It helps clarify certain conceptual patterns that emerge from NE.
Plus, it provides a direct functor for the evolutionary algorithm(s) using a
lambda calculus.  However, it is a pain to learn (it isn&#39;t taught very well
and the lexicon approaches gibberish).  I&#39;ve found it very helpful.



Many times in various domains, models are actually categories of weak models
(more specifically, graphs, manifolds, toposes). We use NE to evolve our
models (quantum, nano, and meso phenomena) for cycles of forward and inverse
(Bayesian) and use the evolved open ended fitness functions (not always
knowing what those functions &quot;mean&quot;).



When analyzing data structure, it may range from regular (HyperNEAT is good
at regularity), up to approaching an amorphous shape (more computationally
expensive).



Re: randomness - it depends on information embedded in the search pattern.
If you&#39;re not familiar with the technique, look up Adaptive Stochastic
Resonance.



I&#39;ll take a look at the kaggle site, and see if anything aligns with my
work.



