Hi all,

I&#39;m guessing that many on here will by now be away of the data mining
competition web site - kaggle. If not then I&#39;d recommend checking it
out as there are some interesting data sets being put up there now on
a regular basis.

One of the the main lessons for me from competing in kaggle
competitions has been that no matter which underlying technique I use
to model the data it generally isn&#39;t competitive. To make that leap
into competitive modelling requires ensembles of models. And ensembles
of many weak models can and do result in strong models. In fact the
main method in use on kaggle is Random Forests (ensemble of Decision
Trees), in which each decision tree is generally a really poor model
all by itself - but they are very fast to construct, so you can build
an ensemble of hundreds or thousands in a reasonable span of time.

Si I&#39;d like to throw out some ideas regarding what the EC community
can learn from this, if anything. Does the power of ensembles apply to
EC in any way?

The general approach is to take an underlying technique - for me this
is usually a gradient descent approach - and to apply some randomness
to it, such that each time you run it the model produced will be
different. One of the most common techniques is to use a random
sub-set of the training data to learn against (e.g. bootstrap
aggregation) and/or to use a random sub-set of variables to model.
Basically any sources of randomness you can think of that don&#39;t
completely break the model.

You can imaging that each model in the ensemble is modelling the data
in a slightly different way, but a no less correct way overall (they
all score ok), and therefore when we combine them the errors that each
of them make will tend to be averaged down - making a better overall
model.

I want to apply this idea NEAT but won&#39;t have time to work on it for a
while so I thought I would throw the idea out there for feedback and
maybe it will spark some discussion. My initial thoughts on how this
could apply to NEAT are as follows:

1) Each genome will now be made up of multiple distinct parts, each
part representing a distinct ANN, so basically the new genome is a
collection of traditional NEAT genomes. Lets call the distinct parts
chromosomes for now - maybe there is a better word to use there?

2) We evaluate a genome by decoding each chromosome in turn into a
network and then combing the networks into an ensemble of networks .
Note that this is functionally different to combining them into one
giant network, *if* you allow connections from the output nodes back
into the hidden nodes - that would mean that the sub-networks would be
actually connected up and passing signals between each other.

3) We can put the ensemble behind an interface such as INetwork, such
that existing code that handles and evaluates INetworks(s) continues
as before.

4) When performing crossover we can now choose to do this at the
sub-network level as an extra option. So swap in a different
sub-network(chromosome), or add and remove sub-networks, or add a new
randomly created sub-network.

You might think that this is not qualitatively different to what we
have. The ensemble could be represented with one large ANN and
therefore our existing genome structure (barring the issue about
sharing of output nodes). My suspicion is that there *is* a
qualitative difference here, that because the sub-nets can be copied
in their entirety that they will co-evolve and each will focus on
specific functionality. It also possibly provides another mechanism
for allowing large scale changes to the ensemble ANN that are good and
sound changes, rather than relying on fitness sharing and speciation
to allow a chain of small bad mutations that lead to a larger positive
change.

I could go into this a bit more but hopefully I&#39;ve said enough to
convey the idea.

Thoughts?

Colin

P.S. I figure this approach is orthogonal to much of the current
research such as novelty search and indirect encodings.




