ygrp-msg&gt;&lt;div id=3Dygrp-text&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hi all,&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I&#39;m guessing that many on he=
re will by now be away of the data mining&lt;br&gt;competition web site - kaggle.=
 If not then I&#39;d recommend checking it&lt;br&gt;out as there are some interesting=
 data sets being put up there now on&lt;br&gt;a regular basis.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;One of the =
the main lessons for me from competing in kaggle&lt;br&gt;competitions has been t=
hat no matter which underlying technique I use&lt;br&gt;to model the data it gene=
rally isn&#39;t competitive. To make that leap&lt;br&gt;into competitive modelling re=
quires ensembles of models. And ensembles&lt;br&gt;of many weak models can and do=
 result in strong models. In fact the&lt;br&gt;main method in use on kaggle is Ra=
ndom Forests (ensemble of Decision&lt;br&gt;Trees), in which each decision tree i=
s generally a really poor model&lt;br&gt;all by itself - but they are very fast t=
o construct, so you can build&lt;br&gt;an ensemble of hundreds or thousands in a =
reasonable span of time.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Si I&#39;d like to throw out some ideas regardi=
ng what the EC community&lt;br&gt;can learn from this, if anything. Does the powe=
r of ensembles apply to&lt;br&gt;EC in any way?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The general approach is to=
 take an underlying technique - for me this&lt;br&gt;is usually a gradient descen=
t approach - and to apply some randomness&lt;br&gt;to it, such that each time you=
 run it the model produced will be&lt;br&gt;different. One of the most common tec=
hniques is to use a random&lt;br&gt;sub-set of the training data to learn against=
 (e.g. bootstrap&lt;br&gt;aggregation) and/or to use a random sub-set of variable=
s to model.&lt;br&gt;Basically any sources of randomness you can think of that do=
n&#39;t&lt;br&gt;completely break the model.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;You can imaging that each model i=
n the ensemble is modelling the data&lt;br&gt;in a slightly different way, but a =
no less correct way overall (they&lt;br&gt;all score ok), and therefore when we c=
ombine them the errors that each&lt;br&gt;of them make will tend to be averaged d=
own - making a better overall&lt;br&gt;model.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I want to apply this idea NE=
AT but won&#39;t have time to work on it for a&lt;br&gt;while so I thought I would th=
row the idea out there for feedback and&lt;br&gt;maybe it will spark some discuss=
ion. My initial thoughts on how this&lt;br&gt;could apply to NEAT are as follows:=
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;1) Each genome will now be made up of multiple distinct parts, each=
&lt;br&gt;part representing a distinct ANN, so basically the new genome is a&lt;br&gt;c=
ollection of traditional NEAT genomes. Lets call the distinct parts&lt;br&gt;chro=
mosomes for now - maybe there is a better word to use there?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;2) We e=
valuate a genome by decoding each chromosome in turn into a&lt;br&gt;network and =
then combing the networks into an ensemble of networks .&lt;br&gt;Note that this =
is functionally different to combining them into one&lt;br&gt;giant network, *if*=
 you allow connections from the output nodes back&lt;br&gt;into the hidden nodes =
- that would mean that the sub-networks would be&lt;br&gt;actually connected up a=
nd passing signals between each other.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;3) We can put the ensemble be=
hind an interface such as INetwork, such&lt;br&gt;that existing code that handles=
 and evaluates INetworks(s) continues&lt;br&gt;as before.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;4) When performi=
ng crossover we can now choose to do this at the&lt;br&gt;sub-network level as an=
 extra option. So swap in a different&lt;br&gt;sub-network(chromosome), or add an=
d remove sub-networks, or add a new&lt;br&gt;randomly created sub-network.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br=
&gt;You might think that this is not qualitatively different to what we&lt;br&gt;hav=
e. The ensemble could be represented with one large ANN and&lt;br&gt;therefore ou=
r existing genome structure (barring the issue about&lt;br&gt;sharing of output n=
odes). My suspicion is that there *is* a&lt;br&gt;qualitative difference here, th=
at because the sub-nets can be copied&lt;br&gt;in their entirety that they will c=
o-evolve and each will focus on&lt;br&gt;specific functionality. It also possibly=
 provides another mechanism&lt;br&gt;for allowing large scale changes to the ense=
mble ANN that are good and&lt;br&gt;sound changes, rather than relying on fitness=
 sharing and speciation&lt;br&gt;to allow a chain of small bad mutations that lea=
d to a larger positive&lt;br&gt;change.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I could go into this a bit more bu=
t hopefully I&#39;ve said enough to&lt;br&gt;convey the idea.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Thoughts?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br=
&gt;Colin&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;P.S. I figure this approach is orthogonal to much of the curr=
ent&lt;br&gt;research such as novelty search and indirect encodings.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/=
